          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Putin surprise vist to Kursk</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/president-vladimir-putin-visit-sudzha-kursk-russia.png" alt="President Vladimir Putin visited Sudzha, Kursk" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>President Vladimir Putin visited Sudzha, Kursk. Credits: AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Russian forces have recaptured Sudzha, a key town in the Kursk region. This marks a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-03-2025-h1-1-significant-symbolic-victory?source=website" target="_blank">significant symbolic victory</a> for Moscow. With a pre-war population of about 5,000, Sudzha was one of the last Ukrainian-held settlements in the area. This threatens Ukraine’s bargaining power amid negotiation pressure to end the war.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">Russia’s defense ministry confirmed the capture, while Ukraine’s military hinted at further tactical retreats to protect its troops. President Putin visited Kursk, urging soldiers to fully "liberate" the region and proposing a buffer zone along the border. Meanwhile, US special envoy Steve Witkoff arrived in Moscow for ceasefire talks, as Ukraine has already accepted a US-backed 30-day truce.
       </p>
        </mj-text>
